Education | Reference.com









































www.reference.com
































Education




Q:

What is standardized testing?



A:
As reported by Procon.com, W. James Popham, former president of the American Educational Research Association, defines a standardized test as "any test that's administered, scored, and interpreted in a standard, predetermined manner." Standardized tests take many forms. Usually, they include multiple-choice questions, which are scored quickly and automatically by machines and computers. 


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Standardized Tests




























Colleges & Universities









Q:
What kind of school campus is conducive to learning?


A:
A democratic environment where students are allowed to pick and choose what they wish to learn is the type of environment that is the most conducive to learning.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Colleges & Universities












Q:
How long does it take to get a master's degree?


A:
A master's degree is usually achieved within 2 years of starting the program, but can take longer or shorter depending on the individual student and the program that they are enrolled in. Some universities offer options for college students to enroll in programs that offer dual degrees where students can get a secondary degree along with their master's degree without taking a break in between programs. These programs can take anywhere from 4 to 10 years.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Colleges & Universities












Q:
What is the difference between a Kappa and a Nupe?


A:
A Kappa and a Nupe both refer to members of the Kappa Alpha Psi fraternity. Both terms mean the same, but how they are used and when they are used is the biggest difference to be found.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Colleges & Universities












Q:
Why would I want to join a sorority?


A:
Sororities encourage one to become involved in the community, develop leadership skills and pursue lifetime goals with passion. The sisterhood that sorority members experience helps females build confidence and lasting friendships that are beneficial throughout their lives. Sorority members are also granted special privileges on and off campus.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Colleges & Universities












Q:
How long is a semester in college?


A:
A college semester generally lasts approximately 15 weeks. This may vary from institution to institution based on factors such as holidays, exam schedules, and other local or state issues.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Colleges & Universities












Q:
What is the age limit for college sports?


A:
There is no age limit imposed by the NCAA on those wishing to play collegiate sports. While there are a multitude of other eligibility requirements, there is no ceiling on how old a player may be.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Colleges & Universities








